Date:11/15/2011 4:46:12 PM
From:J Mako
i am not sure where u got that idea.

graham uses nacv as proxy of liquidation value. in a liquidation, ALL liability
are real liability. so, i am not sure what CA - CL tells u.

those lease obligation are real liability. u just need to imagine u were the
property owner. would u want to recover the contractual payments? in the good
years when property prices are going up, u may argue the vendor is more than
happy to terminate the contract so he can get even better rent. but i always
start with the assumption these are real liabilities and then work from there.
