%BOM---------------------
Date:11/15/2011 6:20:53 PM
From:Jurgis Bekepuris
J Mako,

I don't think I know much more than you do. :) I am not really on the data
center or service deployment side of things. I see some of the stuff that
happens, but I am not directly involved in it. So thoughts below are all
anecdotal. :/

Blade servers - Small companies just do their own rack (or use cloud) and
change things fast as they grow. Midsize companies get into various bizarre
setups since cloud doesn't usually work while homebrew sucks and outsourcing is
not viable either. Big cos that are not technical at core might be getting IBM
setups - I don't really know. Then there are
Googles/Amazons/Facebooks/Microsofts that have teams for building out
data/compute warehouses next to nuclear power stations. ;) Even that changes a
lot, Google has gone through maybe 3-4 iterations of more and more
sophisticated setups in last ~10 years. I know this does not answer your
question really. :/

Services - I think things are pretty sticky until some IT-infra activist
decides to switch things around. Or the operational side of company raises hell
about something. But usually, if you get ORCL stuff or IBM/HP/etc. services
they stick for a while. There is still a lot of spectrum though - things are
very different between employee personal computer SW/services/support,
data/compute centers, HR/admin tech infrastructure, etc. Still even crappy SAP,
ORCL setups last for ages and even replace a simpler/better working products.
%EOM----------------------

