From:J Mako
Yes, yes, yes, I'm aware of this pitfall. That's why I said "as long as the
mgmt doesn't do stupid expansion (i.e. growth) of which return will still be
below their cost of capital" which you've conveniently cut out. :-)

Correct me if I'm wrong:

Company 1 - ROE 8% - P/B 0.5
Company 2 - ROE 16% - P/B 1

When both company pay out all the earnings as dividends, both companies don't
grow and both give the investor the same return. So, high ROE is important when
it's a growing company.

If I'm correct, we are on the same page.

p.s. Of course, there are a lot of caveats in reasoning with ROE and growth. I
have reservation on the assumption that Growth = Retention Rate x EPS x ROE.

